Many local variants of the Greek alphabet were employed in ancient Greece during
the archaic and early classical periods, until they were replaced by the
classical 24-letter alphabet that is the standard today, around 400 BC. All
forms of the Greek alphabet were originally based on the shared inventory of the
22 symbols of the Phoenician alphabet, with the exception of the letter Samekh,
whose Greek counterpart Xi (Î) was used only in a sub-group of Greek alphabets,
and with the common addition of Upsilon (Î¥) for the vowel /u, Å«/. The local, so-
called epichoric, alphabets differed in many ways: in the use of the consonant
symbols Î§, Î¦ and Î¨; in the use of the innovative long vowel letters (Î© and Î),
in the absence or presence of Î in its original consonant function (/h/); in the
use or non-use of certain archaic letters (Ï = /w/, Ï = /k/, Ïº = /s/); and in
many details of the individual shapes of each letter. The system now familiar as
the standard 24-letter Greek alphabet was originally the regional variant of the
Ionian cities in Asia Minor. It was officially adopted in Athens in 403 BC and
in most of the rest of the Greek world by the middle of the 4th century BC.
